# MCP tool conventions

These conventions apply to two surfaces:

1. The `mcp/` subpackage inside every scraper repo (`linkedin-go/mcp/…`,
   `x-go/mcp/…`, …).
2. `agent-setup/backend/internal/mcp/` (transport, registry, response
   shaper) and `agent-setup/backend/internal/mcp/platforms/` (per-platform
   bindings).

The `mcptool` package (`github.com/teslashibe/mcptool`) is the shared
contract. Treat it as upstream — update there first when behaviour needs to
change for every package.

## Tool definition (per-package `mcp/`)

- ALWAYS use `mcptool.Define[*pkg.Client, InputT]` to construct tools. Do
  not hand-write `mcptool.Tool{}`. `Define` reflects the JSON schema from
  `InputT` so it can never drift from the Go input.
- `Name` is `"<platform>_<verb>_<noun>"` in snake_case
  (e.g. `linkedin_search_people`, `x_create_tweet`). Verbs are imperative.
- `Description` is one sentence ≤ 120 chars, ending with a period. Mention
  pagination/limits if relevant.
- `WrapsMethod` is the bare method name on `*Client` (e.g. `"SearchPeople"`).
  Empty only for tools that aggregate or wrap a package-level function.
- Define one `InputT` struct per tool. Use `json` and `jsonschema` tags:

  ```go
  type SearchPeopleInput struct {
      Query string `json:"query" jsonschema:"description=keywords or name,required"`
      Limit int    `json:"limit,omitempty" jsonschema:"minimum=1,maximum=50,default=10"`
  }
  ```

  `default=10`, `minimum=1`, `maximum=50` are the agent-setup-wide
  defaults. Tools that page natively should keep them in sync.
- Group tools by domain in separate files (`search.go`, `profile.go`, …)
  and assemble them in `mcp.go` via `Provider.Tools()`.

## Excluded methods (`excluded.go`)

Every method on `*Client` must be either wrapped by a tool or listed in
`Excluded` with a one-line reason:

```go
var Excluded = map[string]string{
    "SetUserAgent":  "configuration helper, not user-callable",
    "Close":         "lifecycle method owned by the host",
}
```

The package's `mcp_test.go` must run
`mcptool.AssertCoverage(t, &pkg.Client{}, Provider{}.Tools(), Excluded)` so
adding a new method without exposure breaks CI.

## Response shaping

- Prefer **summary shapes** for list endpoints: `{id, title, author,
  score, created_at}` — full object via a separate `get_*` tool.
- Use `mcptool.PageOf[T]` for paginated list responses (returns
  `{items, next_cursor, truncated}`).
- Truncate long free-text fields with `mcptool.TruncateString(s, 800)`.
- Prefer `omitempty` on every JSON-tagged field in response structs so
  null/empty values don't waste tokens.
- Never call `log.Printf` from tool handlers — return structured errors so
  the agent can act on them.

## Errors

- Return `*mcptool.Error{Code, Message, Retryable, Data}` for everything
  the user/agent can act on. Generic Go errors map to `internal_error`.
- Codes are snake_case lowercase (e.g. `credential_expired`, `rate_limited`,
  `not_found`, `invalid_input`). Reuse existing codes before inventing new
  ones.
- Set `Retryable=true` only for transient infra errors. Setting it for
  bad input causes infinite agent loops.
- Use `Data` for actionable hints (e.g. `{"reconnect_url":
  "/settings/platforms/linkedin"}`).

## agent-setup wiring (`internal/mcp/platforms/`)

- A new platform is one entry in `platforms.All()` plus one factory
  function in this file. Do not import scraper packages from anywhere else
  in agent-setup.
- The `NewClient` factory must:
  - Parse the credential blob with `parseCredential`.
  - Validate every required cookie/token field explicitly with a typed
    error (`return nil, errors.New("X credential missing 'foo'")`).
  - Construct the upstream client with the verified inputs only — never
    silently fall back on empty values.
- The `Validator` paired with the binding must check the same required
  fields with cheap structural checks (no network calls). Network-level
  validation happens lazily inside `NewClient` at first tool call.
- Platform IDs are lowercase snake_case (`x_viral`, `reddit_viral`,
  `producthunt`). They are used in URLs (`/api/platforms/:platform/...`)
  so they must be URL-safe.

## Transport (`internal/mcp/transport.go`)

- The MCP route group is `/mcp/v1` (JSON-RPC 2.0 over HTTP). Per-user
  paths use `/mcp/u/:token/v1`; the JWT in `:token` is validated by
  `auth.RequirePathAuth("token")`.
- Response shaping is applied uniformly by `ResponseShaper` in
  `internal/mcp/shape.go` — do not duplicate truncation logic in tools or
  in the transport.
- New JSON-RPC methods go in `Transport.dispatch`. Keep them thin; real
  logic belongs on `Server`.

## Cursor agent etiquette

- When you add a method to a scraper `*Client`, you must in the same PR
  either (a) add a tool that wraps it, or (b) add it to `Excluded` with a
  reason. Don't merge red.
- When you change a tool's input struct, bump the package's minor
  version. Schema is part of the wire contract.
- Run `go test ./mcp/...` after any tool/`*Client` change.
